questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;National Policy on Education, 1968&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;National Policy on Education, 1968&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This was the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;first policy&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; in India to recommend that public expenditure on education should constitute &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;6% of the GDP&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The policy emphasized the need for education to be a priority area for national development and to allocate adequate resources for its growth.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It laid the foundation for the idea that &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;education expenditure&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; should be linked to the overall economic growth of the country.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Subsequent Policies&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;National Policy on Education, 1986&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; reaffirmed the recommendation of allocating 6% of GDP to education but did not achieve this target.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Revised NPE-Program of Action, 1992&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; also highlighted the importance of public expenditure on education but reiterated the challenges in achieving the 6% target.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;National Education Policy, 2020&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The NEP 2020 once again emphasized the need to increase public investment in education to reach the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;6% of GDP&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; target.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This policy aimed to overhaul the Indian education system and stressed the importance of financial support for its successful implementation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Match the LIST-I with LIST-II&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;table data-path-to-node=&quot;2&quot;&gt;
	&lt;thead&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;LIST-I (Commission on Education)&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;LIST-II (Major Recommendation)&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/thead&gt;
	&lt;tbody&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;A. The Education Commission (Kothari Commission)&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;I. Setting up of the University Grants Commission&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;B. University Education Commission (Radhakrishnan Commission)&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;II. 12th Class should be attached to the university&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;C. The Knowledge Commission&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;III. Creation of Indian Educational Services&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;D. Secondary Education Commission (Mudaliar Commission)&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;IV. Establishing an independent Regulatory Authority for Higher Education&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Choose the correct answer from the options given below:&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;A-III, B-I, C-IV, D-II&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;The Education Commission (Kothari Commission)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Recommended the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;creation of Indian Educational Services&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; to professionalize educational administration in India.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Aimed at ensuring uniformity and quality in educational governance across states.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;University Education Commission (Radhakrishnan Commission)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Suggested the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;setting up of the University Grants Commission (UGC)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; to regulate and maintain standards in higher education.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Focused on improving the quality of university education in India.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;The Knowledge Commission&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Proposed &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;establishing an independent Regulatory Authority for Higher Education&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; to enhance autonomy and innovation in universities.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Focused on reforms to make India a knowledge-based economy.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Secondary Education Commission (Mudaliar Commission)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Recommended that the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;12th class should be attached to universities&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; to streamline secondary education with higher education.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Aimed at bridging the gap between secondary and higher education systems.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Kothari Commission (1964-66)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Known as the National Education Commission, it was chaired by Dr. D. S. Kothari.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Its recommendations led to the formulation of the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;National Policy on Education, 1968&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Radhakrishnan Commission (1948-49)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Chaired by Dr. Sarvepalli Radhakrishnan, it focused on higher education reforms.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Stressed the importance of research and academic freedom in universities.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Knowledge Commission (2005-09)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Established by the Government of India under Dr. Sam Pitroda.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Focused on reforms in education, research, and innovation to build a knowledge-driven society.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Mudaliar Commission (1952-53)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Chaired by Dr. Lakshmanaswami Mudaliar, it emphasized secondary education reforms.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Recommended diversification of courses and vocational education at the secondary level.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
Choose the correct statement regarding Vedic education:&lt;br /&gt;
A. In the Vedic period, education was the responsibility of the state.&lt;br /&gt;
B. No fees were charged from students.&lt;br /&gt;
C. Gurukuls were in a poor state because they received no designated funding from the state.&lt;br /&gt;
D. The Samavartana ritual was performed at the end of Buddhist and Jain education.&lt;br /&gt;
E. After the Vedic Upanayana ritual, all students were called Pabbaja and Samanera.&lt;br /&gt;
Select the correct answer from the options given below:

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;Only B and C&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;No fees were charged from students&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Vedic education system&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, education was provided free of cost. The students lived in the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;gurukul&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; and served their guru as a form of gratitude.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Students were expected to live a simple life, reflecting the values of discipline and austerity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Poor funding of Gurukuls&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Gurukuls did not receive designated funding from the state, and their maintenance depended on voluntary contributions from society.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This lack of formal financial support often left the Gurukuls in a poor state, relying largely on donations from wealthy individuals or the community.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Vedic education responsibilities&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Vedic period&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, education was primarily the responsibility of the guru, not the state. Gurukuls were private institutions run by individual teachers.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The role of the state in education was minimal, and the focus was on spiritual, moral, and intellectual development.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Samavartana ritual&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Samavartana ritual&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; was a ceremony performed at the completion of &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Vedic education&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, not Buddhist or Jain education. It marked the student&amp;rsquo;s readiness to re-enter society.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Upanayana and student titles&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;After the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Upanayana ritual&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; in the Vedic tradition, students were referred to as Brahmacharis, not Pabbaja or Samanera, which are terms associated with Buddhist monastic education.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Which of the following are the highest seats of learning in Ancient India?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;1) Nalanda&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;2) Takshasila&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;3) Vikramasila&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;4) Odontopuri&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;There were leading centres of Education in the form of Universities in Ancient India which even attracted worldwide students due to its excellent Teaching methodologies and renowned faculties.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ancient Universities were mostly spread across the Northern India which received royal patronage from the kingdoms in which they were situated.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;   background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;Odontopuri&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It was established in the 8th century by Pala Ruler Dharmapala.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;it was a Buddhist Vihara and one of the 6 Buddhist Universities of ancient India.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Odantapuri was considered the second oldest of India&amp;#39;s universities.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Acharya Sri Ganga of Vikramshila was a scholar at this University.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;According to the Tibetan records, &lt;strong&gt;there were about 12,000 students at Odantapuri&lt;/strong&gt; which was situated at a mountain called Hiranya Prabhat Parvat and by the bank of the river Panchanan.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It was destroyed under the siege of Khilji rulers around 1193.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;   background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;Takshasila&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It was credited to be the world&amp;#39;s first University situated at the ancient site of Taxila (modern-day Punjab province of Pakistan).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It flourished from 600 BC-500AD.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Subjects taught were grammar,philosophy,medicine,politics,warfare,astronomy,commerce,music,vedas.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;More than 10,500 students from all over the world studied here.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Renowned Teachers of this University includes Kautilya, Panini, Jivak and Vishnu Sharma.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Arthashastra (the text on administration and statecraft) by Kautilya was written here.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;India&amp;#39;s first emperor Chandragupta was a student of Takshila University.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;   background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;Vikramshila&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;nbsp;Founded by King Dharmapala in late 8th century or early 9th century.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;It was one of the largest Buddhist University having more than 100 Teachers and about ten thousand students.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It was a centre to spread Buddhist learning across foreign countries.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;nbsp; The most distinguished eminent scholar of this university was Atisa Dipankara, the founder of Lamaism in Tibet.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Subjects like theology, philosophy, grammar, metaphysics, logic were taught here.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Tantrism was an important branch of learning at Vikramshila University.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It proposed for about 4 centuries meeting its collapse in the 13th century AD.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is located near Bhagalpur District of Bihar.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;   background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;Nalanda University&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It was established during the reign of Kumaragupta.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;built by Narasimha Deva in the 6th century BC&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Nalanda was a completely residential university believed to have 2,000 teachers and 10,000 students.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It had 10 temples, meditation centres and greatest library of the world divided into 3 buildings- Ratnasagara, Ratnaranjaka and Ratnadadhi&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Most renowned departments were Mathematics and Astronomy&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The famous scholar of this university was Harshavardhana, Dharmpal, Vasubandhu, Nagarjuna, Padmasambhava and Xuanzang.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Therefore,&amp;nbsp;we can conclude that Nalanda, Takshasila, Vikramasila, and Odontopuri all these universities are the highest seats of learning in ancient India.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ministry of Tribal Affairs&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Ministry of Tribal Affairs is responsible for the overall development and welfare of India&amp;#39;s tribal populations.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It formulates policies, programs, and schemes to promote the economic and social development of tribal communities.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The NISHTHA (National Initiative for School Heads and Teachers Holistic Advancement) capacity-building programme aims to improve the quality of school education through integrated teacher training.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The collaboration with NCERT (National Council of Educational Research and Training) aims to enhance the professional development of teachers and principals in Eklavya Model Residential Schools (EMRS), which cater to tribal students.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ministry of Skill Development and Entrepreneurship&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This ministry is responsible for coordinating all skill development efforts across the country.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It aims to remove the disconnect between demand and supply of skilled manpower, build the vocational and technical training framework, skill upgradation, and build new skills.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ministry of Minority Affairs&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This ministry is responsible for the development and welfare of minority communities in India.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It implements various schemes and programs for their socio-economic development, educational empowerment, and protection of their cultural and linguistic identity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ministry of Education&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This ministry is responsible for the development of human resources in India, primarily through the formulation of policies, planning, and administration of education in the country.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It oversees both school and higher education and implements various schemes aimed at improving literacy rates and educational standards.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;NCERT (National Council of Educational Research and Training)&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;NCERT is an autonomous organization under the Ministry of Education.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It assists and advises the central and state governments on academic matters related to school education.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;NCERT develops curriculum and textbooks, educational kits, and digital materials to improve the quality of school education.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;Dr. B.R. Ambedkar Open University&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dr. B.R. Ambedkar Open University:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Established in 1982, Dr. B.R. Ambedkar Open University (BRAOU) was the first open university in India.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Located in Hyderabad, Telangana, it aims to provide educational opportunities to all segments of society.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The university offers various undergraduate, postgraduate, and certificate courses through distance learning mode.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It uses a multimedia approach for teaching, combining print, audio, and video materials.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
